04712nam a22007575i 9780271089034DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710890347 a10.1515/97802710890342doi  a(DE-B1597)585056  a(OCoLC)1244618344  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0150702bisacsh04a745.6/7009022231 aGertsman, Elina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Absent Image :bLacunae in Medieval Books /cElina Gertsman. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b58 color/62 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Nothing Is the Matter -- tChapter one. Imaginary Realms -- tChapter two. Phantoms of Emptiness -- tChapter three. Traces of Touch -- tChapter four. Penetrating the Parchment -- tCoda. Absences -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGuided by Aristotelian theories, medieval philosophers believed that nature abhors a vacuum. Medieval art, according to modern scholars, abhors the same. The notion of horror vacui—the fear of empty space—is thus often construed as a definitive feature of Gothic material culture. In The Absent Image, Elina Gertsman argues that Gothic art, in its attempts to grapple with the unrepresentability of the invisible, actively engages emptiness, voids, gaps, holes, and erasures.Exploring complex conversations among medieval philosophy, physics, mathematics, piety, and image-making, Gertsman considers the concept of nothingness in concert with the imaginary, revealing profoundly inventive approaches to emptiness in late medieval visual culture, from ingenious images of the world’s creation ex nihilo to figurations of absence as a replacement for the invisible forces of conception and death.Innovative and challenging, this book will find its primary audience with students and scholars of art, religion, physics, philosophy, and mathematics. It will be particularly welcomed by those interested in phenomenological and cross-disciplinary approaches to the visual culture of the later Middle Ages.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAbsence in art. 0aEmptiness (Philosophy) in art. 0aIllumination of books and manuscripts, Medieval. 0aManuscripts, Medieval. 0aNothing (Philosophy) in art. 7aART / History / Medieval.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2021z9783110753790oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2021 Englishz978311075403208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074510840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271089034?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271089034423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271089034/original  a978-3-11-074510-8  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075403-2  EBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2021  aZDB-23-DPKb2021